05291nam a22007455i 9780748679898DE-B159720220629043637.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||220629t20222008stk    fo  d z      eng d  a97807486798987 a10.1515/97807486798982doi  a(DE-B1597)614971  a(OCoLC)1306540126  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  astkcGB-SCT 7aHIS0150002bisacsh04a941.10692231 aBrown, S J, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut14aThe Union of 1707 :bNew Dimensions: Scottish Historical Review Supplementary Issue /cS J Brown, Christopher Whatley. 1aEdinburgh : bEdinburgh University Press, c[2022] 4c©2008  a1 online resource (192 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tCONTENTS -- tPreface -- tContributors -- tChapter 1 The Issues Facing Scotland in 1707 -- tChapter 2 The Union of 1707 and the War of the Spanish Succession -- tChapter 3 Intellectual Capital in Pre-1707 Scotland -- tChapter 4 Conceptions of Nationhood in the Anglo-Scottish Union Debates of 1707 -- tChapter 5 Publicity, Parties and Patronage: Parliamentary Management and the Ratification of the Anglo-Scottish Union -- tChapter 6 The Kirk, Parliament and the Union, 1706–7 -- tChapter 7 A Union for Empire? Scotland, the English East India Company and the British Union -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThis collection brings together a series of papers that in May 2007 were presented at a Royal Society of Edinburgh conference organised to mark the 300th anniversary of the Union of 1707. One of the guiding objectives of the RSE event was to showcase the work of younger historians, and to present new work that would provide fresh insights on this defining moment in Scotland's (and the United Kingdom's) history.The seven chapters range widely, in content and coverage, from a detailed study of how the Church of Scotland viewed union and how concerns about the Kirk influenced the voting behaviour in the Scottish Parliament, through to the often overlooked broader European context in which the British parliamentary union - only one form of new state formation in the early modern period - was forged. The global War of the Spanish Succession, it is cogently argued, influenced both the timing and shape of the British union. Also examined are elite thinking and public opinion on fundamental questions such as Scottish nationhood and the place and powers of monarchs, as well as burning issues of the time such as the Company of Scotland, and trade. Other topics include an investigation of the particular intellectual characteristics of the Scots, a product of the pre-Union educational system, which it is argued enabled professionals and entrepreneurs in Scotland to meet the challenges posed by the 1707 settlement. As one of the contributors argues, union offered the Scots only partial openings within the empire.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Jun 2022) 4aScottish Studies. 7aHISTORY / Europe / Great Britain / General.2bisacsh1 aBowie, Karin, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aJackson, Clare, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMackillop, Andrew, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aPatrick, Derek J., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aSaville, Richard, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aStorrs, Christopher, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aWhatley, Christopher A., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aWhatley, Christopher, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEdinburgh University Pres